    9. Something About You — Eyedress (chords: F, Em, Am, Dm)
    10. Marsha — Current Swell (chords: Dm, C, G, F, Bb)

    Priority 2 — Used in specific levels:
    11. Sunset Garage — Sun Room (chords: G, Em, C, D)
    12. I Didn't Know — Skinshape (chords: Bbmaj7, F, G / Gm, C, A7, Dm)
    13. Texas Sun — Khruangbin feat. Leon Bridges (chords: Am, G / Em, Bm)
    14. Rules — Khruangbin (chords: G, Am, F, Em)
    15. Peace Blossom Boogy — Babe Rainbow (chords: D, G7, A)
    16. 1999 — NO CIGAR (chords: E, B, F#, A)
    17. It's a Love — Baskervillain (chords: E, A, C#m, F#, B)
    18. Surf Hat — Surf Hat (chords: E7, A7, B7, F#7)
    19. Son of a Beach — The Polarity (chords: F, G, C, Am)
    20. Coastline — Hollow Coves (chords: G, Bm, A — capo 2, original CGDGGD tuning)

    Priority 3 — Additional songs if time allows:
    21-50: The remaining tracks from the student's top 50 (I can provide these if you get through the first 20)

    How This Will Be Used

    Your analysis will be directly inserted into guitar exercise descriptions. For example, instead of a generic exercise that says:

    ▎ "Play Am-D with a relaxed strum"

    We want exercises that say:

    ▎ "Play Am-D with a soft pick attack, behind the beat, with ghost strums on the downbeats creating a quiet 'chk-chk' underneath the offbeat chord hits. Listen to how Angus Stone
     lets the Am ring slightly longer than the D — the Am gets 3 beats of sustain, the D gets a quicker muted chop. Match that asymmetry."

    That level of specificity is what we're after. The chord progressions are already verified — what we need from you is everything ELSE.

    Important Notes

    - If you can't determine something from the audio, say "UNCLEAR — would need isolated guitar track to confirm" rather than guessing
    - If the guitar is buried in the mix, note that
    - If there are multiple guitar parts, describe each one separately
    - The student is a beginner-to-intermediate guitarist, so describe techniques in accessible language
    - These songs span genres: indie, surf-rock, psych, reggae, soul, desert blues, folk, afrobeat — adjust your analysis vocabulary accordingly

